In article <1994Aug3.061417.9184@qiclab.scn.rain.com>,
Leonard Erickson <Leonard.Erickson@f51.n105.z1.fidonet.org> wrote:
>Figure out how long it'll take a 486 or a Vax to crank thru all
>possible combos of K1 & k2. Plaintext is *very* recognizable. So
>I can have the program only dump out the stuff that closely resembles
>it. 

For properly chosen N1 & N2 a brute force key search will
be intractable.  For the toy sample I showed, brute force
is tractable, but if this were to be used as a "real"
system one would choose N1,N2 of at least 20 (thus the
work factor would be in the vicinity of 2**120).

